class Solution {
    public int longestDecomposition(String text) {
        int n = text.length();
        if (n == 0) return 0;
        for (int l = 1; l <= n / 2; l++) {
            if (text.substring(0, l).equals(text.substring(n - l))) {
                return 2 + longestDecomposition(text.substring(l, n - l));
            }
        }
        return 1;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^2)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Greedy recursion: always peel off the shortest matching prefix/suffix pair, then recurse on the middle. This maximizes k by creating as many pairs as possible. Substring comparisons are O(n) each, but the greedy choice ensures minimal overlap and optimal splits.

